    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load metric.csv, trace.csv, log.csv, and error_logs.csv. For each file, return a compact summary only: 1) total number of rows; 2) min(timestamp) and max(timestamp); 3) top 20 most frequent cmdb_id values with their counts. Additionally, from metric.csv return the top 20 kpi_name values with counts; from trace.csv return the top 20 trace_name values with counts; from log.csv return the top 20 log_name values with counts. Limit all lists to at most 20 entries."
}

{
    "analysis": "The Executor returned file-level summaries for metric.csv, trace.csv, log.csv and empty error_logs.csv. Key observations: 1) metric.csv covers 16:30–17:30 (UTC+8) and contains many container/node KPIs, notably many metrics for node-6. 2) trace.csv and log.csv are focused on the incident window (17:00–17:30 UTC+8) and show heavy activity from frontend pods and checkoutservice, productcatalogservice, recommendationservice, cartservice, and currencyservice. 3) error_logs.csv is empty. From these summaries we cannot yet identify faults; next we should detect metric anomalies during the incident window. Specifically, we should compute global thresholds (P95) per (cmdb_id, kpi_name) using each series' full available data, then check anomalies within 2022-03-20 17:00–17:30 (UTC+8). We'll focus on components that appear in trace.csv (since traces identify active services) to keep the search bounded.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From metric.csv: 1) extract the set of unique cmdb_id values that appear in trace.csv (use trace.csv's cmdb_id column). 2) For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) pair where cmdb_id is in that set, compute the global P95 threshold using all available rows for that pair in metric.csv. 3) Filter metric.csv rows to the time window 2022-03-20 17:00:00 to 2022-03-20 17:30:00 (UTC+8) and for each (cmdb_id,kpi_name) pair compute: total_points_in_window, anomaly_count (rows where value >= global P95), earliest_anomaly_timestamp (smallest timestamp where value >= P95), max_value_in_window, and the P95 threshold. 4) Return the top 20 (cmdb_id,kpi_name) pairs ranked by anomaly_count (descending). For ties, rank by earliest_anomaly_timestamp ascending. Limit output to those columns only."
}

{
    "analysis": "The previous Executor run found many metric \"anomalies\" concentrated on adservice-0 where global P95 for many KPIs is 0.0, causing all-zero samples to be flagged. This is likely a false-positive artifact (metrics with zero baseline). Metrics-only analysis at this point is noisy; we should use traces and logs next to localize failures because traces capture service interactions and error rates/durations. Specifically, we need to: 1) compute global thresholds for trace features (P95 and P5) using the full trace.csv; 2) detect high-side anomalies (>=P95) and low-side anomalies (<=P5) within the incident window 2022-03-20 17:00:00 to 2022-03-20 17:30:00 (UTC+8); 3) return compact aggregates (counts and earliest timestamps) so we can identify which services/traces show sustained anomalies and at what times. This will narrow candidates for the two failures.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using trace.csv: 1) For each (cmdb_id, trace_name) compute global P95 and P5 using all available rows in trace.csv. 2) Filter rows to the window 2022-03-20 17:00:00 to 2022-03-20 17:30:00 (UTC+8). For each (cmdb_id, trace_name) in that window compute: total_points_in_window, count_high = number of rows with value >= global P95, earliest_high_timestamp (first timestamp where value >= P95 or null), count_low = number of rows with value <= global P5, earliest_low_timestamp (first timestamp where value <= P5 or null), max_value_in_window, min_value_in_window, p95, p5. 3) Return the top 20 (cmdb_id, trace_name) pairs ranked by max(count_high, count_low) desc, then by earliest_high_timestamp or earliest_low_timestamp asc. Limit output to these columns only."
}

{
    "analysis": "Trace analysis returned mostly constant 0.0 values with global P95/P5 = 0.0, so trace signals are uninformative for fault localization. Metric analysis earlier flagged many adservice-0 KPIs as \"anomalous\" because their global P95 = 0 produced false positives for zero-valued series. We therefore need to move to log analysis to find concrete error occurrences and timestamps that can point to the two failures. The next step should compactly identify which components reported non-zero log.error_count (or other non-zero log metrics) within the incident window and when the first non-zero events occurred.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From log.csv: filter rows to the window 2022-03-20 17:00:00 to 2022-03-20 17:30:00 (UTC+8). For each (cmdb_id, log_name) compute: total_points_in_window, nonzero_count (value != 0), earliest_nonzero_timestamp (first timestamp with value != 0 or null), max_value_in_window. Return up to top 20 rows ordered by nonzero_count descending, then earliest_nonzero_timestamp ascending. Limit output to these columns only."
}

{
    "analysis": "Previous steps: 1) File summaries showed metric.csv spans 16:30–17:30 and contains many container/node KPIs (node-6 prominent). 2) Metric anomaly scan flagged many adservice-0 KPIs as \"anomalous\" but that was driven by global P95 == 0.0 so those are false positives. 3) Trace analysis was uninformative because many trace metrics are constant 0.0 (P95 and P5 = 0.0). 4) Log analysis revealed many services produced consistent non-zero log.row_count throughout the window; earliest non-zero events are at 2022-03-20 17:00:00+08:00 for all top candidates (cartservice, currencyservice, frontend, productcatalogservice, recommendationservice, shippingservice, adservice, checkoutservice, emailservice, etc.).\n\nWhat we can derive so far: traces and many metrics are zero-valued and unhelpful; logs indicate elevated activity across many services starting at 17:00, but log.row_count alone doesn't indicate root-cause reason. We need to find metric KPIs with meaningful deviations from their global baselines (not the zero-baseline artifacts). To narrow down, we should inspect metric KPIs for the services that showed non-zero logs and look for KPIs whose values significantly exceed their global P95 (i.e., breach >50% of extremal), then record earliest breach time(s). These breaches are stronger candidates for faults and will give occurrence times and reasons (CPU/memory/disk/network).",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using metric.csv, consider the following cmdb_id list (top log candidates): [cartservice-0, cartservice-1, cartservice-2, currencyservice-0, currencyservice-1, currencyservice-2, frontend-1, frontend-2, productcatalogservice-0, productcatalogservice-1, recommendationservice-1, recommendationservice-2, shippingservice-1, adservice-0, adservice-1, adservice-2, checkoutservice-0, checkoutservice-1, emailservice-0, emailservice-2]. For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) pair where cmdb_id is in that list: 1) compute global P95 using the full series for that pair across metric.csv; 2) filter rows to the window 2022-03-20 17:00:00 to 2022-03-20 17:30:00 (UTC+8) and compute total_points_in_window, breach_count where value >= 1.5 * P95 (skip pairs where P95 == 0), earliest_breach_timestamp (first timestamp with value >= 1.5*P95), max_value_in_window, and the P95. 3) Return the top 20 (cmdb_id,kpi_name) pairs with breach_count > 0 ordered by breach_count desc then earliest_breach_timestamp asc. Limit columns to: cmdb_id, kpi_name, total_points_in_window, breach_count, earliest_breach_timestamp, max_value_in_window, p95. If no pairs have P95 > 0 (or no breaches), return an empty result indicating that metric-based breaches were not found for these candidates."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have progressively narrowed candidates. Metric breach scanning with a 1.5x-P95 rule (skipping P95==0) revealed several meaningful breaches: most notably adservice-1 memory_failures at 2022-03-20 17:05:00+08:00 (breach_count=2, p95=49.5, max=99) and adservice-2 memory_failures at 2022-03-20 17:27:00+08:00 (breach_count=2, p95=82.5, max=363). Other candidates (cartservice network spikes, frontend memory_failures at 17:15, single breaches in currency/checkout/shipping/mesh metrics) are present but have lower severity/frequency. Trace aggregates restricted to the candidate set showed non-zero row_count traces for adservice-1, adservice-2, and cartservice-0 across the window but did not show large duration spikes; trace evidence is neutral but confirms traffic reached adservice pods. Log.row_count is non-zero across many services starting at 17:00, so logs alone are noisy. Given the metric severity (memory_failures with large absolute values and repeated breaches) and their distinct times, the strongest candidates for the two failures are: (1) adservice-1 memory failure event around 2022-03-20 17:05+08 and (2) adservice-2 memory failure event around 2022-03-20 17:27+08. To confirm exact occurrence timestamps and get corroborating evidence, we must retrieve the precise metric rows that breached the 1.5*P95 criterion for adservice-1 and adservice-2 memory_failures within the 17:00–17:30 window.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using metric.csv: For cmdb_id in [\"adservice-1\",\"adservice-2\"] and kpi_name containing \"container_memory_failures\", compute the global P95 for each (cmdb_id,kpi_name) using the full available series. Then filter rows to the window 2022-03-20 17:00:00 to 2022-03-20 17:30:00 (UTC+8) and return all rows where value >= 1.5 * P95. Return columns: timestamp, cmdb_id, kpi_name, value, p95. Limit output to top 20 rows."
}

{
    "analysis": "The Executor returned four substantive metric breaches in the incident window: two consecutive spikes for cartservice-2 at 2022-03-20 17:12:00 and 17:13:00 (value≈0.3477 MB vs p95≈0.1020), and two consecutive spikes for cartservice-0 at 2022-03-20 17:19:00 and 17:20:00 (value≈0.3442/0.3400 MB vs p95≈0.0961). Earlier analysis (filtered, P95>0, 1.5×P95 rule) also identified a clear adservice-1 container_memory_failures spike at 2022-03-20 17:05:00+08 (value 82.5, p95 49.5). Metric and trace data confirm traffic reached adservice pods; logs show widespread non-zero row_count but adservice error_count was 0 in-window. \n\nWhat this implies: adservice-1 at 17:05 is a high-confidence fault (container memory failure). The second failure candidate is a network receive MB spike on cartservice: both cartservice-2 and cartservice-0 show short, consecutive spikes exceeding 1.5×P95, which meet the fault-identification criteria (not isolated single-sample noise and amplitude >> threshold). To finalize the second failure as a true fault and assign the exact component and time, we must corroborate with logs/traces for cartservice to see whether error events or trace error_rate/duration anomalies align with the network spikes (i.e., around 17:12–17:13 for cartservice-2 and 17:19–17:20 for cartservice-0).\n\nConclusion so far: probable failures are (A) adservice-1 memory failure at 2022-03-20 17:05:00+08 (container memory failure), and (B) a cartservice network receive spike (either cartservice-2 at ~17:12 or cartservice-0 at ~17:19). We need log/error corroboration to choose which cartservice spike corresponds to the second failure.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From log.csv: filter to window 2022-03-20 17:00:00 to 2022-03-20 17:30:00 (UTC+8) and cmdb_id in [\"cartservice-0\",\"cartservice-2\"], log_name == \"log.error_count\". For each cmdb_id compute: total_points_in_window, nonzero_count (value != 0), earliest_nonzero_timestamp (first timestamp with value != 0 or null), and max_value_in_window. Return up to 2 rows (one per cmdb_id) with these columns only."
}

